concept_explanation.pattern:
**Sliding Window — when to use:**

```
Use sliding window when:
1. Looking at CONTIGUOUS subarray/substring
2. Window has a SIZE constraint or INVARIANT to maintain
3. You can efficiently ADD (expand right) and REMOVE (shrink left)

Fixed size window (size = k):
  1. Build first window [0..k-1]
  2. Slide: add nums[hi], remove nums[hi-k]
  3. Track max/min/sum as you slide
  O(n) time, O(1) space

Variable size window (until condition met):
  lo = 0;
  for (hi = 0; hi < n; hi++) {
    // EXPAND: add s.charAt(hi) to window
    while (windowInvalid()) {
      // CONTRACT: remove s.charAt(lo)
      lo++;
    }
    // window is now valid — update answer
    answer = Math.max(answer, hi - lo + 1);
  }
  O(n) time — lo never moves backward, total moves ≤ n
```

worked_example.final_code:
int lo=0, maxLen=0;
Set<Character> window=new HashSet<>();
for(int hi=0; hi<s.length(); hi++) {
    while(window.contains(s.charAt(hi))) {
        window.remove(s.charAt(lo++)); // shrink left
    }
    window.add(s.charAt(hi));
    maxLen=Math.max(maxLen, hi-lo+1);
}
return maxLen; // O(n) time, O(min(n,charset)) space
